WEBVTT

00:02.000 --> 00:05.686
A vacancy has appeared
and you're going to fill it.

00:06.000 --> 00:08.924
From now on, Mr Shelby,
you shut your gypsy mouth

00:09.000 --> 00:10.923
and listen to your instructions.

00:11.160 --> 00:14.767
<i>I know it was you who carried
out the murder of Mr Duggan.</i>

00:15.000 --> 00:19.642
--You are on my hook, Mr Shelby.

00:20.360 --> 00:22.806
- Name?
-Harold Hancox.

00:22.880 --> 00:25.008
- Have you ever been arrested?
-No.

00:25.080 --> 00:26.923
Arthur, we can stand him up.

00:27.440 --> 00:30.250
<i>Last night, one of our men had
his throat cut in Winston Green.</i>

00:30.320 --> 00:31.845
I'm not real!

00:31.920 --> 00:35.970
Gentlemen? This is your cousin.
Polly's son, Michael.

00:36.040 --> 00:38.520
- I want to go with them.
-Over my dead body.

00:38.600 --> 00:40.921
Do we hear 800 guineas? 850.

00:41.000 --> 00:43.731
<i>May Carleton.
I breed racehorses and train them.</i>

00:43.800 --> 00:46.485
- So will you consider me?
-I will consider you.

00:46.760 --> 00:48.330
Thomas Shelby?

00:51.920 --> 00:53.524
<i>Did they behave themselves?</i>

00:53.800 --> 00:56.167
They were really amazing.

00:59.800 --> 02:09.787
<b><font color="#004F8C">Ripped By mstoll</font></b>

02:46.760 --> 02:50.207
You might think this is a curious
place for me to suggest a meeting,

02:50.840 --> 02:52.808
but...

02:52.880 --> 02:55.486
your surprises have only just begun.

03:05.880 --> 03:08.690
You look a little unsteady, Mr Shelby.

03:09.400 --> 03:11.050
Take a seat.

03:17.520 --> 03:18.760
You're working together.

03:20.360 --> 03:23.011
Blowing up the Garrison was your idea.

03:24.240 --> 03:26.004
You chose me.

03:29.920 --> 03:33.003
It's funny, I thought the
Fenians had a policy...

03:33.080 --> 03:34.809
- Enough.
-Eh? Of not mixing

03:34.960 --> 03:36.086
the personal with the political.

03:36.160 --> 03:37.366
- I said enough.
-I think

03:37.440 --> 03:39.010
I will decide on what is enough.

03:39.080 --> 03:41.651
Who's in charge here then, eh?
Who's in charge?

03:41.920 --> 03:44.241
Right, let me understand this.

03:44.320 --> 03:47.085
- You answer to an agent of the Crown.
- Perhaps we can just...

03:47.160 --> 03:50.050
- Very interesting.
-Perhaps we can stick to the agenda.

03:50.120 --> 03:52.566
- Whose agenda?
-There is a form of words here.

03:52.640 --> 03:54.529
- Whose words?
-Arrogant bastard.

03:56.120 --> 03:57.963
I'm not accustomed
to being spoken to like that.

03:58.080 --> 03:59.206
just come to order.

03:59.280 --> 04:01.567
I am here to listen,
but not to the fucking infantry.

04:01.640 --> 04:03.881
Enough! Jesus!

04:03.960 --> 04:05.405
Now...

04:07.520 --> 04:11.161
Some weeks ago, Mr Shelby
carried out a military mission

04:11.240 --> 04:15.131
on behalf of pro-treaty Republicans
here in Birmingham.

04:15.200 --> 04:16.440
You...

04:16.519 --> 04:18.329
Working for the King.

04:18.399 --> 04:21.721
- There is a unique political situation.
-Yea h? How does that feel?

04:22.280 --> 04:24.328
- Let us...
-Tell me. How does that fucking feel?

04:24.400 --> 04:25.686
...stick to the form of words.

04:25.760 --> 04:28.081
- Temporarily, we have a shared interest.
-Oh, I see.

04:28.160 --> 04:30.322
- Shall we just stop him laughing?
-You want me to stop laughing?

04:31.560 --> 04:32.891
Explain this, pal.

04:33.080 --> 04:35.208
Following the success of your mission...

04:35.320 --> 04:37.766
- We're going to make you do it again.
-Will you shut up?

04:37.840 --> 04:40.207
Can we just conduct
ourselves here, please?

04:40.280 --> 04:41.805
- Conduct ourselves!
-Please.

04:41.880 --> 04:45.521
No one in this room wants to breathe
the same air as anyone else.

04:48.280 --> 04:50.965
- Nevertheless...
-Nevertheless the pro-treaty Paddies

04:51.040 --> 04:53.088
and the King want the same man dead.

04:54.880 --> 04:56.450
Am I right?

05:18.800 --> 05:21.610
- Why him?
-Did you ask why in France?

05:22.520 --> 05:26.889
- Yeah.
-So, it's the same answer, because.

05:33.840 --> 05:35.251
Why me?

05:36.200 --> 05:38.521
- Because.
-Because.

05:41.560 --> 05:43.289
Because if anybody connects me to this,

05:43.400 --> 05:45.846
it will be assumed
that it was a criminal act

05:45.960 --> 05:47.769
and not a political one.

05:47.840 --> 05:51.447
No, you need not fear being
connected to the killing

05:51.520 --> 05:54.888
because I will see to it that
no connection is ever made.

05:55.440 --> 05:58.364
You will have complete
immunity after the fact.

05:58.920 --> 06:02.766
But, in the execution, you will get
no help from agents of the Crown.

06:03.200 --> 06:04.565
And we can't be seen to be involved.

06:06.760 --> 06:09.730
You have been chosen, Mr Shelby,

06:10.240 --> 06:11.810
and there really is no choice.

06:12.080 --> 06:14.367
No equals bang,

06:14.440 --> 06:17.205
and your man here will shed no tears
as he looks the other way.

06:23.160 --> 06:24.730
Nevertheless...

06:25.520 --> 06:26.806
I say no.

06:33.400 --> 06:35.607
Mr Shelby?

06:41.000 --> 06:44.209
What about your export licence,
Mr Shelby?

06:44.280 --> 06:46.726
You had a deal with Mr Churchill.

06:52.240 --> 06:55.244
The one with the mouth,
Donal Henry, he is a spy.

06:55.640 --> 06:58.211
He is working for the Irregulars
against the pro-treaty Paddies.

06:58.320 --> 07:00.527
He reports every fucking
word back to them.

07:00.600 --> 07:01.806
No, it's not possible.

07:01.880 --> 07:04.645
They've both been security vetted
by my own department.

07:04.720 --> 07:07.087
I have men in places your men can't go.

07:07.200 --> 07:10.044
Donal Henry meets the
anti-treaty Paddies in the back room

07:10.160 --> 07:13.528
of the Mother Red Cap in Saltley,
sometimes twice a week.

07:14.800 --> 07:17.451
These Irish enemies are
fucking brothers and cousins.

07:17.520 --> 07:20.364
You are stepping into a world
you don't understand.

07:24.000 --> 07:27.846
If what you're saying is true,
he'll be dealt with.

07:27.920 --> 07:32.482
Bring me proof the spy is dead
and we have a deal.

07:49.440 --> 07:50.601
Mr Shelby.

07:50.800 --> 07:52.404
- Billy boy.
-Watch it.

08:00.280 --> 08:02.169
Now on you go.

08:54.720 --> 08:57.724
Right. boys, let's go!

09:31.320 --> 09:33.163
Fuck you!

09:33.240 --> 09:35.083
Mario!

09:36.360 --> 09:38.169
Mario!

09:45.320 --> 09:47.687
Mario!

09:47.760 --> 09:49.489
Come here.

09:53.600 --> 09:56.206
Sabini's day is done.

09:57.880 --> 09:59.564
I'll protect you now.

10:02.120 --> 10:03.724
Oh, shut up!

10:04.120 --> 10:06.361
Stop fucking whingeing.

10:08.120 --> 10:11.408
Due to my razor blade,

10:11.480 --> 10:14.563
and a few complaints from the neighbours

10:14.640 --> 10:17.450
about the terrible fucking music...

10:22.520 --> 10:25.729
Do you want to tell them or should I?

10:25.800 --> 10:29.361
This place is under new management.

10:35.040 --> 10:38.089
<i>By order of the Peaky Blinders.</i>

12:25.680 --> 12:27.045
Yes?

12:28.400 --> 12:29.970
Somebody to see you, Mr Shelby.

12:30.040 --> 12:31.883
He says he's come about the
position of accounts clerk.

12:32.960 --> 12:34.644
Send him in.

12:37.760 --> 12:40.491
- just through here, sir.
- Thank you.

12:44.520 --> 12:45.965
Michael...

12:48.160 --> 12:49.764
Vacancy's been filled.

12:52.560 --> 12:54.642
Not according to this morning's paper.

13:03.120 --> 13:05.122
At school, I was top of the
class in mathematics,

13:05.240 --> 13:08.210
and I did a night school course in
accountancy at Worcester College.

13:10.960 --> 13:12.564
Mum says you've had
six different accountant clerks

13:12.640 --> 13:13.971
in the last six months.

13:16.200 --> 13:20.000
When respectable men see the
other things you do, they leave.

13:21.760 --> 13:25.207
But I, like Lizzie out there,
already know what you do.

13:27.920 --> 13:31.208
Mum says you want to be 80% legal
within two years.

13:31.280 --> 13:33.521
- Three.
-I can help.

13:35.160 --> 13:38.767
I know both sides and
you know you can trust me.

13:40.080 --> 13:44.449
I want to help you, Tommy, become legal.

13:46.400 --> 13:48.289
Do the right thing.

13:52.240 --> 13:53.810
I want to be proud of this family.

14:01.560 --> 14:03.130
Does Polly know you're here, Michael?

14:05.440 --> 14:07.204
I'm 18 on Friday, I go where I please.

14:23.720 --> 14:25.404
You phone your mother.

14:28.400 --> 14:30.004
Good luck.

14:38.760 --> 14:41.127
We're not open for winnings yet.

14:41.320 --> 14:43.129
I'm here to see Thomas Shelby.

14:48.120 --> 14:50.248
I have an appointment.

14:50.320 --> 14:51.970
Come in.

15:05.040 --> 15:07.520
- May Carleton.
- Mr Shelby has his proper meetings

15:07.600 --> 15:09.568
in his other office.

15:11.040 --> 15:13.850
This was the address that he gave me.

15:13.920 --> 15:16.605
- He gave you this address?
-He said it was a gambling den.

15:17.800 --> 15:19.564
I told him that I'd wanted to see one

15:19.640 --> 15:21.369
since I'm always reading
about them in the papers.

15:22.000 --> 15:24.844
Quite the big scandal
in The Telegraph lately.

15:24.920 --> 15:27.890
Anyway, he said that
I could come and have a look.

15:30.960 --> 15:32.371
And now I feel like a bit of an idiot

15:32.440 --> 15:34.568
because I'm early and he's late
and I have no idea how to behave.

15:35.160 --> 15:36.525
In a gambling den?

15:39.000 --> 15:41.526
I'll wait in the car.

15:41.600 --> 15:44.080
If I open the door again,
they'll all want to come in.

15:45.520 --> 15:47.204
Like flies.

15:51.880 --> 15:53.006
So what are you?

15:54.080 --> 15:55.809
What am I?

15:55.880 --> 15:57.370
To Thomas?

15:59.000 --> 16:02.447
I'm going to train his racehorse...
For Epsom.

16:03.560 --> 16:05.005
You know horses?

16:06.320 --> 16:08.891
Yes. You?

16:08.960 --> 16:10.246
Born riding.

16:11.640 --> 16:14.405
I slept in a manger when I was a baby.

16:16.080 --> 16:17.889
I was born riding, too.

16:21.640 --> 16:24.291
There's a fucking
great Riley parked out there

16:24.360 --> 16:25.646
and nobody's watching it.

16:25.720 --> 16:29.805
John, this woman says
she's training Thomas' horse.

16:33.240 --> 16:34.969
He's told us a lot about you.

16:37.160 --> 16:38.650
Don't know where he is, do you?

16:42.720 --> 16:45.166
Sorry I'm late.
There was a family matter.

16:45.240 --> 16:47.049
Esme, keep it locked up for a minute.

16:47.160 --> 16:49.766
- Yes, Thomas.
-I'll show you around.

16:57.880 --> 17:00.929
So, be my guest.

17:11.119 --> 17:13.202
That's my brother Arthur's office.

17:17.760 --> 17:19.728
Down there is my brother John's office,

17:19.800 --> 17:22.406
that's where we slate
the runners and the riders.

17:25.560 --> 17:28.369
It's so out in the open.
What about the police?

17:29.680 --> 17:31.170
What about them?

17:33.360 --> 17:36.443
When I drove into Small Heath,
I thought I was going to get murdered...

17:36.680 --> 17:38.682
Then I mentioned your name.

17:40.200 --> 17:42.328
It was like being escorted
to see a king.

17:45.680 --> 17:48.365
- You came here to get my girl, right?
-Right.

18:04.040 --> 18:05.530
She looks in very good condition,

18:05.600 --> 18:07.921
considering she's not been
out on the gallops.

18:08.120 --> 18:10.009
Curly's the best horseman in England.

18:10.080 --> 18:12.651
I have a man called Mickey
who'd argue the point.

18:12.720 --> 18:15.200
Ah, Curly here is half horse himself.

18:15.280 --> 18:17.442
She's blessed. Very blessed.

18:17.520 --> 18:19.409
Well, she's from the best stock.

18:19.920 --> 18:21.922
But I'd rather have a coloured pony.
Mixed blood is stronger.

18:22.640 --> 18:24.210
Not to win the Derby, Curly.

18:24.280 --> 18:26.328
Don't like them racing, Tommy,
not the way they beat them.

18:26.800 --> 18:29.531
- She's all yours.
-Thank you.

18:33.120 --> 18:34.849
He gets sad when one leaves.

18:35.560 --> 18:38.848
- What time is your box van coming?
-Midday.

18:38.920 --> 18:41.810
Maybe you've got time to take
the lady to the Garrison,

18:41.880 --> 18:43.689
show her the spa and the tearooms.

18:46.080 --> 18:48.003
I'd like that, why not?

18:54.520 --> 18:58.047
I just had it done up.
There was a fire.

18:58.120 --> 18:59.645
It's...

18:59.720 --> 19:02.166
Yeah.

19:02.240 --> 19:03.730
What do you drink?

19:04.960 --> 19:06.724
So early, but gin.

19:23.560 --> 19:25.130
Goodness. With something?

19:27.920 --> 19:29.524
Like what?

19:30.960 --> 19:32.485
Tonic water or...

19:34.200 --> 19:37.568
Erm... We have, erm...

19:37.720 --> 19:39.006
Cordial.

19:40.560 --> 19:42.085
There's not much room in there but...

19:53.560 --> 19:55.403
You want to fuck me, Mrs Carleton?

19:58.160 --> 19:59.889
Perhaps because I...

20:00.400 --> 20:03.085
Perhaps because I would represent
something to you?

20:05.120 --> 20:07.487
We should have this conversation
before the booze

20:08.360 --> 20:10.010
starts talking for us.

20:13.160 --> 20:14.571
You have a horse.

20:16.720 --> 20:18.609
Yes, I have a horse.

20:19.240 --> 20:21.720
The horse is why I'm here.

20:23.040 --> 20:24.405
Purely that.

20:25.160 --> 20:28.209
And because you're paying me a
lot of money to train your horse,

20:28.280 --> 20:29.770
that's why I'm here.

20:30.360 --> 20:31.646
Purely that.

20:35.680 --> 20:37.284
Good.

20:38.320 --> 20:40.163
Good. Well, a toast, then.

20:40.960 --> 20:42.849
To the horse, to the Derby.

20:47.080 --> 20:48.809
- Cheers.
-Cheers.

20:53.880 --> 20:56.042
So is that what you say to women?

20:59.240 --> 21:00.924
Only if I don't know what they want.

21:01.720 --> 21:03.768
And what if they don't want to fuck?

21:05.240 --> 21:07.322
Then life is simpler.

21:07.400 --> 21:08.970
You want a simple life?

21:13.000 --> 21:15.765
Do I look like a man
who wants a simple life, eh?

21:17.120 --> 21:18.565
So what do you want?

21:21.000 --> 21:23.731
For what I'm paying you, Mrs Carleton,

21:23.920 --> 21:27.845
I want a horse that'll pay out
at Epsom on an each-way bet.

21:33.720 --> 21:36.690
Before I took your account,

21:37.200 --> 21:38.645
I did some credit checks on you.

21:40.680 --> 21:43.365
Apparently, you don't exist.

21:48.840 --> 21:50.842
My existence is questionable.

21:53.520 --> 21:55.443
Gypsies don't like registers.

21:56.800 --> 22:00.725
You see, I'm not gypsy like you mean.

22:00.800 --> 22:02.723
But you did register for France.

22:04.680 --> 22:06.682
I also sent your name to the War Office,

22:07.280 --> 22:09.521
I have friends there.

22:09.600 --> 22:11.841
You won two medals for gallantry.

22:14.120 --> 22:17.329
Does that really impress you,
Mrs Carleton?

22:21.760 --> 22:23.205
Call me May.

22:30.200 --> 22:32.123
Charlie says the box Van's here.

22:33.320 --> 22:34.890
Thank you, Finn.

22:38.080 --> 22:40.208
You know, I still don't know what
you're going to call your horse.

22:43.200 --> 22:46.283
The horse will be called Grace's Secret.

22:48.960 --> 22:50.564
Grace's Secret.

22:56.720 --> 22:59.610
I told him he definitely
can't take the job.

23:01.160 --> 23:03.766
He said, "All right,
I'll move to London, then."

23:03.840 --> 23:07.686
I said, "I won't give in to blackmail.
No is no."

23:09.160 --> 23:12.403
Well... That settles it, then.

23:13.520 --> 23:16.285
I'll give the job
to the other candidate.

23:16.360 --> 23:18.328
He's much better qualified anyway.

23:18.400 --> 23:22.166
Michael did City and Guilds, six months.

23:22.240 --> 23:24.402
Yeah, but he doesn't know racing, Poll.

23:25.280 --> 23:28.409
He knows horses,
but he doesn't know racing.

23:28.800 --> 23:30.962
This other boy, he knows racing.

23:31.040 --> 23:32.929
He's good. He's a fast learner.

23:36.280 --> 23:38.362
What if Michael really leaves?

23:39.720 --> 23:41.882
You just got to let him go, Poll.

23:41.960 --> 23:44.611
He'll get a job in an office in London.

23:44.680 --> 23:46.170
I'm sure he'll write to you.

23:47.160 --> 23:48.730
He made a big speech

23:48.800 --> 23:53.169
about wanting to help you
build up a respectable business.

23:53.240 --> 23:55.004
Oh, he's like his dad,
he could make me cry.

23:55.480 --> 23:57.050
There are trains to London.

23:58.400 --> 23:59.890
So I just let him leave?

24:00.400 --> 24:02.289
Every month or so he'd be back.

24:03.600 --> 24:05.523
Unless, of course, he meets a girl.

24:05.880 --> 24:07.723
Then, who knows?

24:13.080 --> 24:14.889
Oh, my God.

24:16.360 --> 24:18.010
You want him to do this job.

24:18.080 --> 24:21.084
Polly, I want what you want.

24:22.760 --> 24:26.162
What about this other more
qualified candidate?

24:26.880 --> 24:29.008
Mmm...

24:29.080 --> 24:30.684
Well, I lied, there isn't one.

24:35.640 --> 24:37.244
How much you paying?

24:38.760 --> 24:40.888
- The advertised rate.
-Like hell.

24:41.680 --> 24:43.648
- Three bob.
-Like hell.

24:44.720 --> 24:46.449
- Three and six.
-Four.

24:47.840 --> 24:49.365
Four it is.

24:55.000 --> 24:56.889
- I love him, Tom.
-I know.

24:57.520 --> 25:00.649
That's why I'll keep him away
from the old business,

25:00.720 --> 25:03.121
put him charge of the new. Agreed?

25:04.280 --> 25:05.850
Agreed.

25:15.240 --> 25:17.925
Well, Finn, you've got two choices,
mild or mild.

25:18.600 --> 25:21.080
- Mild.
-There you go.

25:21.160 --> 25:23.686
--Here he is, look.

25:27.800 --> 25:29.404
Happy birthday, Michael.

25:29.520 --> 25:32.410
Eighteen years old. You're a man today.

25:32.480 --> 25:33.766
Give him a drink, John boy.

25:33.880 --> 25:35.166
- There you go, lad.
-And after that,

25:35.600 --> 25:37.682
we'll go to find you
a lady of the night.

25:37.760 --> 25:38.966
Arthur!

25:42.800 --> 25:44.768
Michael.

25:44.840 --> 25:46.444
What's that?

25:46.760 --> 25:48.728
So you're never late for work.

25:53.120 --> 25:55.407
Welcome to the business,
Michael.

25:55.480 --> 25:58.723
- Welcome to the business.
-Thank you.

25:58.800 --> 26:00.882
Right, come on, let's get him drunk.
Come here, you.

26:00.960 --> 26:02.166
All right, whisky.

26:02.240 --> 26:06.325
No whisky, he's at work tomorrow.
Give him only dark mild.

26:06.400 --> 26:07.447
A toast.

26:07.800 --> 26:09.290
- Toast.
- To Michael.

26:09.360 --> 26:10.964
To Michael.

26:28.200 --> 26:29.850
You all right?

26:38.360 --> 26:40.886
- What is it?just us?
-just us.

26:40.960 --> 26:42.291
We celebrating?

26:43.800 --> 26:45.211
just taste this.

27:00.360 --> 27:01.771
What do you think, Arthur?

27:01.840 --> 27:05.401
Yeah, it's good.
Good stuff, really nice.

27:05.480 --> 27:07.403
Too good for the Garrison.

27:07.480 --> 27:10.848
I suppose we could shift it
to the toffs at the Eden Club.

27:11.480 --> 27:13.005
Why? What is it?

27:13.520 --> 27:15.284
That is part of an export drive.

27:16.880 --> 27:19.770
We now have a secure warehouse
in Camden Town

27:19.840 --> 27:22.764
and secure passage to the Poplar Docks.

27:22.840 --> 27:24.683
So, on Monday morning,

27:24.760 --> 27:27.525
we'll be sending out
our first export crates.

27:27.600 --> 27:31.241
A crate of Riley car spa res,

27:31.360 --> 27:33.408
bound for Halifax, Nova Scotia.

27:34.240 --> 27:35.810
Where there's prohibition.

27:37.320 --> 27:38.890
Where there is prohibition.

27:40.120 --> 27:42.009
All over Canada and America,

27:42.200 --> 27:45.044
people are making their own booze
in bathtubs.

27:45.160 --> 27:50.371
But rich people in New York,
in Toronto and Boston

